[2] Treatment, comment
Date: Tue 17 Feb 2015
From: Fabrice Simon <simon-f@wanadoo.fr> [edited]


Re: French guidelines on case management of chikungunya-infected patients (acute, post-acute, and chronic stages)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A recent ProMED-mail post on chikungunya in the Americas (archive no 20150210.3156702) mentioned a recent paper on an uncontrolled therapeutic experiment. The moderator TY commented on it: "One case is anecdotal but interesting, but will be of limited value until a statistically valid clinical trial is carried out." We totally agree with him about this kind of experimentation. To date, there is no drug available to heal all chikungunya [virus]-infected patients. Many drugs (vitamin C, phytotherapy, allopathy) have been tested in few regular trials and many empirical field experiments, unsuccessfully.

However, physicians must always do their best to provide relief for their patients without adverse effects. We want to stress that it is possible to help most patients with appropriate use of some well-known drugs and physiotherapy.

To avoid such uncontrolled experiments due to the lack of knowledge, the Direction Generale de la Sante of the French Ministry of Health asked the Societe de Pathologie Infectieuse de Langue Francaise (the French Infectious Diseases Society) to produce guidelines for the case management of chikungunya [virus]-infected patients (acute stage and persisting forms). We directed a group of about 20 French experts (infectiologists, rheumatologists, GPs, reeducators, from mainland France, Reunion, Martinique, Guadeloupe, French Guiana) who worked on the topic for months. After having analysed the literature and debated their clinical experience, we produced a consensus among experts that is available online (free access) in French at http://www.infectiologie.com/site/medias/Recos/2014-Chikungunya-recommandations.pdf. We have answered the most frequently asked questions from GPs and listed the adequate practices for acute, post-acute, and chronic stages; some inefficient and/or potentially deleterious treatments are also mentioned.

We think that promoting this information about these French guidelines (English version coming soon) by ProMED could bring significant help for the patients and their physicians.

--
Communicated by:
Dr Fabrice Simon, MD, PhD, and Dr Emilie Javelle, MD
Department of Infectious Diseases and Tropical Medicine, Laveran Military Teaching Hospital
Marseille, France
<simon-f@wanadoo.fr>

[ProMED thanks Drs Simon and Javelle for this comment. The guidelines put together by this group of medical specialists will be very helpful. A version in English is awaited, and one hopes that in addition to French it will also become available in Spanish and Portuguese, because most of the cases in the Americas have occurred in the countries where those are the main languages spoken. - Mod.TY]
